00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:58.180
So people say testing.

00:02:58.180 --> 00:02:59.630
People say quality assurance.

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:01.161
What are they?

00:03:01.161 --> 00:03:03.285
Quality assurance is actually
just a whole process.

00:03:03.285 --> 00:03:05.570
It involves a whole lot of
different types of testing.

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:11.140
But in general, it's
the systematic process

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.360
checking to see whether
a product of service

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:17.290
being developed is meeting
its specified requirements.

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:19.190
The most important
part of that definition

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:21.500
really is systemic,
which means you're doing

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.690
regular, repeatable testing.

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:27.710
Looking at making sure that
all the portions of your game

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:28.920
or project are working.

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:30.660
And requirements,
making sure you're

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:34.700
meeting that it
doesn't just "work"

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:36.310
as far as you think it does.

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:38.370
It works according the
requirements of the game,

00:03:38.370 --> 00:03:40.760
of the project, of
whoever you're shipping

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:42.010
to and et cetera and so forth.

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:44.887
So you need to know what
your standards are to be

00:03:44.887 --> 00:03:46.095
doing good quality assurance.

00:03:50.830 --> 00:03:53.940
Without testing, your
project will fail,

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:57.350
and will take more time, and
will take a lot more effort.

00:03:57.350 --> 00:03:59.740
You can make games
without programmers.

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:02.702
There's a lot of graphical user
interface engines out there.

00:04:02.702 --> 00:04:04.410
Some of them are
getting older and older,

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:06.201
but they're out there
and you can use them.

00:04:06.201 --> 00:04:07.190
GameMaker, for example.

00:04:07.190 --> 00:04:08.350
You can make games
without artists.

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:09.891
I bet several of
you are figuring out

00:04:09.891 --> 00:04:11.330
how to do that right now.

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:13.680
But you can also
make games completely

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:16.890
without assets using text
engines like Inform 7.

00:04:19.184 --> 00:04:21.600
You don't really need designated
producer or distinct game

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:23.290
designer on a small team.

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:25.500
One person can
really do it alone.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.790
But you're never going to make
a good game without testing,

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:31.690
and the more
systemic and planned

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:34.890
your testing is, the
more results you'll

00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:36.210
get from less effort.

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:44.020
So who gets to do
all this testing?

00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:46.960
That's really everyone
involved in the project.

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:49.330
Do not assume that
because you are

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:51.100
the key programmer
or the key designer

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:54.510
or the key whatever that someone
else will check your code

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:58.290
and make sure it's working
after you've integrated it.

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:00.170
You really want
everyone on the team

00:05:00.170 --> 00:05:01.940
to consider it to be
their responsibility

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:04.320
to keep the game working
as well as possible

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:07.120
all the way through, and
also to take the time

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.180
to go in and check
other people's stuff

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:12.080
to make sure that it went in.

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:16.090
Remember that this is one of
the cornerstones of using Scrum

00:05:16.090 --> 00:05:18.990
as well, where before a
task is actually done,

00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:20.800
someone else has gone
in and verified it.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.300
Well, someone else is going to
be someone on the team, which

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:26.620
means you're all going to have
allot some time to doing it,

00:05:26.620 --> 00:05:28.940
and you're going to have
to think about that.

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:32.870
Speaking of which, anybody have
testing as one of your tasks

00:05:32.870 --> 00:05:34.163
on your sprint task list?

00:05:37.950 --> 00:05:39.680
Anybody?

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:41.960
Woo, you win.

00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:43.340
It's going to take some time.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:45.800
And it's going to take some
time that probably otherwise

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.210
could be used for making code.

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:49.720
So go ahead and
remember that now

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:51.219
and think about
that as you're going

00:05:51.219 --> 00:05:53.560
into your last week
of work, that you need

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:57.070
to allot some time for testing.

00:05:57.070 --> 00:05:58.566
So types of testing.

00:05:58.566 --> 00:05:59.940
What is the
terminology I'm going

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:04.550
to use so that we all understand
what I'm saying when I say it?

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:08.230
I divide testing up
into three major areas,

00:06:08.230 --> 00:06:14.240
and there isn't a lot of formal
methodology on this, especially

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:15.930
not in the game industry.

00:06:15.930 --> 00:06:19.170
So I tend to talk about
technical testing, play

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:21.760
testing, and user testing.

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:27.740
When I say technical testing, I
mean getting your game to run.

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:29.910
Specifically, I often
mean getting your game

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:33.070
to run exactly as how
you intended it to run.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:39.940
So if the designer claims that
the peach mobile should go up

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:42.910
to 30 miles per hour and fire
eight peaches per second,

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.630
if you go into the
game and you discover

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:46.500
that it goes 70 miles
per hour and fires

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:48.820
two peaches per
second, that's not

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:52.140
working even if it makes game
awfully fun with it like that.

00:06:55.550 --> 00:06:58.047
When you start thinking
about whether it's fun or not

00:06:58.047 --> 00:07:00.380
as a developer, then you're
moving into the area of play

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:02.980
testing which is
where you, the team,

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:05.200
are playing your game
trying to figure out,

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.622
hey, all those requirements and
constraints and plans we made,

00:07:08.622 --> 00:07:09.330
are they working?

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:12.886
And are they working well, and
is a player going to enjoy it?

00:07:12.886 --> 00:07:14.760
You're play testing your
game as a developer.

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:16.343
You're checking to
make sure it works.

00:07:16.343 --> 00:07:17.140
In that case, yes.

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:18.931
The fact that the peach
mobile is currently

00:07:18.931 --> 00:07:23.250
going 30 miles per hour and it's
so slow that no player is ever

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:25.100
going to want to use it.

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:25.850
That's a bug.

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:27.230
That's a really big bug.

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:29.509
But it's a play testing
bug if your specs say

00:07:29.509 --> 00:07:31.050
it should be going
30 miles per hour,

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:32.370
not a technical testing bug.

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:34.940
And it is good to know the
differences so that you

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:36.650
can know what
you're talking about

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:38.640
and why you're talking about it.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.840
Finally, there's
user testing, which

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:44.800
is getting someone who is not
on your team to play your game.

00:07:47.104 --> 00:07:49.020
You, the developer, while
you do play testing,

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:50.500
can pretend to be
an actual player.

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:52.110
But you are not
an actual player.

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:54.400
You will never be an actual
player for your game.

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:55.790
You know it too well.

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:57.380
You are too close to it.

00:07:57.380 --> 00:07:59.270
You have spent too
many hours playing it.

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:04.860
So you really need to
get someone who has never

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:07.360
seen your game before, ideally,
to come in and sit down

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:09.456
in front of your
game and play it.

00:08:09.456 --> 00:08:11.830
We're going to make pretend
when we run our focus testing

00:08:11.830 --> 00:08:16.360
workshop that your classmates
here are actually good testers.

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.270
Tell you a secret, they're not.

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:20.917
They've seen your game because
they've play tested it before.

00:08:20.917 --> 00:08:22.250
They've heard you talk about it.

00:08:22.250 --> 00:08:23.380
They heard you pitch it.

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:25.860
They might even have worked
on it if they switched teams.

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:27.740
So they're not actually
your ideal testers,

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:29.350
but they are very
convenient testers.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:31.010
So we're going to
use them today.

00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:32.570
And for your next
projects, we're

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:34.240
going to encourage
you-- and, in fact,

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:36.510
require you-- to go out
into the cold, cold world

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:39.850
and find actual testers
who haven't seen your game.

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:40.799
People in your dorms.

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:42.007
People in your other classes.

00:08:42.007 --> 00:08:44.860
Friends, people at
the coffee shop.

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:47.030
Whoever you think will do
the best job of giving you

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:48.071
the information you need.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:53.796
User testing is another
one of those terminologies

00:08:53.796 --> 00:08:55.460
that means a whole lot.

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:57.930
So for my convenience,
I tend to divide it

00:08:57.930 --> 00:09:00.680
up into two kinds of things,
focus testing and "user

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:02.000
testing."

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:03.750
Where "focus testing"
is specifically

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:05.958
when you're sitting down
and you're playing the game,

00:09:05.958 --> 00:09:07.120
looking at how it plays.

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:07.882
Is it fun?

00:09:07.882 --> 00:09:08.840
Are people enjoying it?

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:09.881
Is it challenging enough?

00:09:09.881 --> 00:09:12.320
Are the mechanics interesting?

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.410
Is your game a good game, and
getting that information back

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:16.700
from your players.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:19.940
When user testing,
I tend to use more

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:22.640
for looking at the
usability of your game.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.690
You may have a really,
really fun game,

00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:26.650
but if it takes your
players 12 minutes

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:29.450
to get off your starting page
because they can't figure out

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:31.670
what they're doing
or how to do it,

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:33.990
that's a pretty serious
usability issue.

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:37.040
And you need to figure
that out as well.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:41.035
So just so you know that those
are those two user types.

00:09:41.035 --> 00:09:43.460
It's all user
testing, but having

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:48.010
some granularity to find the
difference is a little useful.

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:51.020
So the basics for technical
testing, which hopefully we

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:54.040
can go through pretty quickly.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:56.830
I suspect that if you guys
have done programming,

00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:57.830
you've done this before.

00:09:57.830 --> 00:09:59.955
If you've had classes that
wanted code that worked,

00:09:59.955 --> 00:10:03.420
hopefully they've helped teach
you what the good things to do

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:04.490
are.

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:07.610
A lot of this sounds an
awful lot like good software

00:10:07.610 --> 00:10:10.160
practices lecture
that Andrew gave,

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:13.440
because a lot of good testing
is, in fact, a good software

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:14.190
practice.

00:10:14.190 --> 00:10:18.240
So have some
technical standards.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:19.350
Have a bug database.

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:21.140
Or, given the size
of these projects,

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:24.620
at least a bug Excel spreadsheet
with a list of everything

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:26.320
that you've noticed.

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:28.130
Build and test before
checking it in.

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:29.110
Have daily builds.

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:32.190
Have a daily play-through.

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:33.910
Planned feature cuts.

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:34.760
Scope.

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:36.960
When you realize that you're
not getting everything

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:41.550
done on Friday night as
you're working on your game,

00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:43.410
start cutting then.

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:46.050
Don't wait until
Sunday night to decide

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:47.540
what you're going to cut.

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:50.980
Cut as soon as you realize that
you're blowing your estimates.

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:53.380
That will allow you
to choose what you cut

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:55.700
and to adjust
changes in your game

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:57.980
to reflect the things you cut.

00:10:57.980 --> 00:11:00.260
It will also mean
that testing your game

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:03.560
to make sure-- it will
introduce a lot fewer bugs

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:06.280
when you do it in a controlled
manner than when you do it

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:10.700
in desperation, which is
why I put it under testing.

00:11:10.700 --> 00:11:13.030
Finally, code freezes
and asset freezes.

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:14.612
These are great,
and no one likes

00:11:14.612 --> 00:11:16.070
to use them because
it means you're

00:11:16.070 --> 00:11:20.060
going to waste an entire day
not working on your game.

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:21.809
Who wants to do that?

00:11:21.809 --> 00:11:24.100
On the other hand, has anybody
here turned in a project

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:26.750
that they've made a last
minute change to Sunday night,

00:11:26.750 --> 00:11:29.245
it was due Monday morning,
and then it didn't run at all?

00:11:32.472 --> 00:11:33.930
I got some honest
people out there.

00:11:33.930 --> 00:11:35.860
Good.

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:38.255
The advantage of taking that
whole day to test your game

00:11:38.255 --> 00:11:42.926
is you turn something
in that works on Monday.

00:11:42.926 --> 00:11:44.300
Often, you turn
in something that

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:46.217
works a lot better on
Monday because you've

00:11:46.217 --> 00:11:47.300
taken the time to test it.

00:11:47.300 --> 00:11:48.460
You've found the bugs.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:50.970
You've had a friend help you
review your code changes,

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:52.760
and you really got it working.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:56.950
If you want to make a
good, polished, solid game,

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:59.630
you will think about
it and give yourself

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:02.440
a cushion for project two.

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:03.760
That's probably maybe a day.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:04.760
It's a two week project.

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.801
If you give yourself much
more cushion than that,

00:12:06.801 --> 00:12:08.600
you're not actually
working on it.

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:11.270
But actively give
yourself that deadline

00:12:11.270 --> 00:12:13.930
and give yourself some
time to play your game.

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:20.070
So that's the basics.

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:22.370
Some advanced tips.

00:12:22.370 --> 00:12:23.610
It's all pretty simple.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:25.460
I think you've all
heard this all.

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:28.084
How we maintain
your feature list.

00:12:28.084 --> 00:12:29.750
Agree on how features
are going to work,

00:12:29.750 --> 00:12:31.536
so talk with each other.

00:12:31.536 --> 00:12:33.285
Test those features
as soon as they go in.

00:12:36.064 --> 00:12:37.730
This may not be worth
it on these games,

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:39.000
because they're small.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.860
When you hit your
project four game,

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:42.840
you may want to
have one of these.

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:45.420
Think about having a
standardized test plan that

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:48.470
runs through all the buttons
and the branches and the pages

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:50.890
and the options of your game.

00:12:50.890 --> 00:12:52.660
I realize that when
you've got randomness

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:55.160
as one of your
core design goals,

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:57.237
you can't predict how your
game is going to play.

00:12:57.237 --> 00:12:59.320
But you should be able to
take a look at your game

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:01.900
and know most of the states
that it's going to get in.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:04.150
And you can create a
checklist that says, hey,

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:06.275
have we exhausted
all the possibilities

00:13:06.275 --> 00:13:09.810
that a player will encounter?

00:13:09.810 --> 00:13:13.370
Have we tested them all in the
last two builds, yes or no?

00:13:13.370 --> 00:13:14.870
And the answer
should probably there

00:13:14.870 --> 00:13:18.202
be yes because one
of the things that's

00:13:18.202 --> 00:13:19.660
very common with
projects that have

00:13:19.660 --> 00:13:22.520
a lot of highly integrated
systems working together

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:25.260
and depend on emergent
behavior-- which

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:28.520
is most games-- is you can
introduce a feature over

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:31.750
here that changes the way that
a feature that you implemented

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:33.250
two weeks ago works.

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:36.350
And you'll never know that it
did that until you go through

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:38.930
and you test and you find that
something that was working

00:13:38.930 --> 00:13:40.530
is now broken.

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:42.690
So it is worth it
to take the time

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:44.370
to go back and
check those features

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:45.760
you know nobody touched.

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:51.610
Bug reporting.

00:13:51.610 --> 00:13:55.430
Because so many people
are so bad at this,

00:13:55.430 --> 00:13:58.100
I'm going to take the time
with a captured audience

00:13:58.100 --> 00:14:01.200
to tell you how to do it.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:02.680
Be kind to your
fellow engineers.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:05.570
Be kind to yourself, if you
end up getting your own bugs.

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:09.190
Write good defect
reports and not bad ones.

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:14.527
Good bugs include what happened,
what should have happened.

00:14:14.527 --> 00:14:16.110
Because it doesn't
do me a lot of good

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:17.609
if you tell me that
the peach mobile

00:14:17.609 --> 00:14:19.310
is going 30 miles
per hour if I don't

00:14:19.310 --> 00:14:20.393
know why that's a problem.

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:24.892
How do I reproduce it?

00:14:24.892 --> 00:14:27.350
If it's obvious to reproduce,
you don't need to include it.

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:31.470
But if it took 38 steps,
include a text file.

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:32.440
How common is the bug?

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:33.850
How serious is the bug?

00:14:33.850 --> 00:14:36.480
Is this something that the team
needs to jump on right now,

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:39.250
or is this something that
Sunday afternoon you're

00:14:39.250 --> 00:14:42.180
going to look at and
say, eh, ship it.

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:45.159
Because some bugs you look
at and you say, eh, ship it.

00:14:45.159 --> 00:14:46.700
But you want to know
that it's there,

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:48.480
and you want to
know how it's going

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:53.385
to affect your game before
you just decide to ship it.

00:14:53.385 --> 00:14:55.760
Include some supporting data
if it's going to be helpful,

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:56.540
and it often is.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:58.540
If you're trying to
describe something visually,

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:00.620
give them a screenshot.

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:02.160
If you can run it
in the debugger

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:05.820
and catch some
debugging code, great.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:06.610
Save the files.

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:08.930
Know the version of the
game you were using.

00:15:08.930 --> 00:15:10.650
Be ready to help
your team member who

00:15:10.650 --> 00:15:13.510
has to fix your horrible awful
crash that happens one out

00:15:13.510 --> 00:15:17.970
of every four times, and you're
not sure how you made it.

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:19.920
Be willing to help
them recreate it,

00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:23.680
because it can be really
hard to recreate bugs.

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:28.310
Finally, know the difference
between a criticism

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:32.000
and a critique, and make
sure that your reports are

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.050
critiques of the
game and the bugs

00:15:35.050 --> 00:15:38.610
and not criticisms of
your fellow developers

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:40.080
and their ideas.

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:42.420
And when I say criticism,
what I mean here

00:15:42.420 --> 00:15:44.915
is an unsupported
opinion usually delivered

00:15:44.915 --> 00:15:47.030
in an unprofessional tone.

00:15:47.030 --> 00:15:50.160
These purple elephants are
junk and it's totally stupid

00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:52.940
that they fly.

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:55.270
A critique is a
statement of opinion

00:15:55.270 --> 00:15:59.400
about the game backed up by
examples and hopefully facts.

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:02.280
The purple elephants
make the game too easy

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:03.500
because they can fly.

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:06.490
I can skip almost a
third of the game play

00:16:06.490 --> 00:16:08.330
in the bottom area
of the screen.

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:09.250
There's a problem.

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:10.810
There's a reason
why it's a problem.

00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:13.107
And there's a fact that
you can talk about,

00:16:13.107 --> 00:16:14.190
and you can have opinions.

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:17.241
And it doesn't matter that the
purple elephants go in the game

00:16:17.241 --> 00:16:17.740
or not.

00:16:17.740 --> 00:16:20.170
You can just talk about what
they're doing in the game.

00:16:20.170 --> 00:16:21.961
You don't have to talk
about the person who

00:16:21.961 --> 00:16:24.670
put the purple elephants
in the game at all.

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:29.080
So user testing.

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.790
I think we've actually
covered this one to death.

00:16:31.790 --> 00:16:35.370
But if I did a
lecture about testing

00:16:35.370 --> 00:16:37.630
and didn't stop and talk
about why you're doing it,

00:16:37.630 --> 00:16:39.420
it would be a little odd.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:42.530
Once again, every time we
say iterative design, that

00:16:42.530 --> 00:16:45.720
means you make a design, you
test it, you get the data,

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:48.300
you move on without actually
testing it with users.

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:52.140
You don't get real data,
et cetera and so forth.

00:16:52.140 --> 00:16:54.840
So I think that drum has
been well and truly beaten.

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:57.320
But here's a warning
we haven't really

00:16:57.320 --> 00:17:01.980
talked about yet, which
is test-driven design.

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:05.960
Does not mean do what your
testers tell you to do.

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:09.790
Test-driven design means
gather data from your testers,

00:17:09.790 --> 00:17:13.420
analyze it, and act on it.

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:15.530
90% of all MIT
students will tell you

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:18.440
that your game is too easy.

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:20.490
They're wrong.

00:17:20.490 --> 00:17:23.000
90% of all people who like
to play first person shooters

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.089
will tell you that
your game needs a gun.

00:17:26.089 --> 00:17:28.310
If you didn't plan on
having a gun in your game,

00:17:28.310 --> 00:17:32.350
it probably really
doesn't need a gun.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:34.722
Testers are often full of
solutions and suggestions

00:17:34.722 --> 00:17:36.430
to make your game just
like the game they

00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:37.554
wish they were playing.

00:17:37.554 --> 00:17:39.220
But you're not trying
to make that game.

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:41.930
You're trying to make the
game you're trying to make.

00:17:41.930 --> 00:17:44.540
So when you gather
your data, put it

00:17:44.540 --> 00:17:47.270
through the filter of what
your vision of the game is

00:17:47.270 --> 00:17:49.250
and what you intend
your game to do,

00:17:49.250 --> 00:17:52.140
and don't let your
testers drive your game.

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:57.240
Let your vision and
your data drive it.

00:17:57.240 --> 00:17:58.390
So how.

00:17:58.390 --> 00:17:59.952
How do you get
ideas from testers?

00:17:59.952 --> 00:18:02.285
And how do you actually turn
them into something useful?

00:18:05.327 --> 00:18:07.160
So you all remember the
experimental method.

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:08.810
It's actually really
pretty similar.

00:18:08.810 --> 00:18:13.050
Going to form a hypothesis,
or ask a question.

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:15.250
Figure out how to get the
data to that question,

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:17.340
collect it, and analyze it.

00:18:17.340 --> 00:18:18.790
So forming a question.

00:18:18.790 --> 00:18:20.740
What do you need to
know about your game

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:23.280
that your team can't answer?

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:26.530
The more specific you
can be, the easier it is.

00:18:26.530 --> 00:18:28.450
Sometimes it is
hard to get specific

00:18:28.450 --> 00:18:29.340
because you've got
a game and you've

00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:30.740
got a whole lot of
interlinking systems,

00:18:30.740 --> 00:18:32.989
and it's hard to figure out
which one is making things

00:18:32.989 --> 00:18:33.870
not quite right.

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:35.420
But do your best.

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:37.310
In there a particular mechanic?

00:18:37.310 --> 00:18:39.650
Are people having a hard
time or an easy time

00:18:39.650 --> 00:18:41.732
getting started on your game?

00:18:41.732 --> 00:18:43.440
How engaged are people
in your game play?

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:45.065
Are they playing the
game and grinning,

00:18:45.065 --> 00:18:47.844
or are they just sitting
there and hitting the keys?

00:18:47.844 --> 00:18:49.635
How many of your players
complete your game

00:18:49.635 --> 00:18:51.260
in about the time
you expected them to?

00:18:51.260 --> 00:18:56.870
How many of them complete
too quickly or take too long?

00:18:56.870 --> 00:18:59.150
So when you're running
scientific experiments,

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:00.800
you try to standardize
your conditions

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:02.860
as much as possible
to get data that can

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:06.300
be compared with each other.

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:09.080
When you're collecting
qualitative data, which

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:10.980
is what most focus
testing data is,

00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:12.730
this is actually pretty
hard to do but you

00:19:12.730 --> 00:19:15.040
want to try to do it anyway.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:20.060
So some of the ways
you can do that is by

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:22.760
make sure you're giving each
player the same set of starting

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:25.716
information by having a
script to introduce your game,

00:19:25.716 --> 00:19:27.840
to give them any information
about the game they're

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:30.600
going to need because your game
is in too early to have a UI.

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:32.590
Games often don't
have UIs that are

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:35.950
particularly useful while
they want to be tested early.

00:19:35.950 --> 00:19:39.780
That's OK, just tell your
players what your UI "should"

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:41.414
tell them.

00:19:41.414 --> 00:19:43.080
You can double this
up with user testing

00:19:43.080 --> 00:19:45.970
by giving them pictures
of the intended UI,

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:48.210
and you can see if they can
figure it out from there

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:48.710
or not.

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:51.730
But that's advanced
testing tricks.

00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:53.725
Have a dedicated observer.

00:19:53.725 --> 00:19:56.100
Don't depend on their memory
for what they're looking for

00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:58.060
or what they see.

00:19:58.060 --> 00:19:59.530
Give them a list
of specific things

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:01.980
to look for that you think
will answer the questions

00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:03.290
you need to answer.

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:05.500
Give them space to
write it down with.

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:07.980
And give them the
autonomy to stand back

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:10.270
and just take notes
while someone else

00:20:10.270 --> 00:20:15.520
offers your player assistance
or introduces them to the game.

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:18.680
And finally, you really
can't observe everything.

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:22.550
Think about what your players
might be able to tell you

00:20:22.550 --> 00:20:23.902
that you can't see.

00:20:23.902 --> 00:20:25.360
Write down a few
questions for them

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:27.470
to answer afterwards
if you need to.

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:28.370
Keep it short.

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:30.578
You don't really want to
make somebody write an essay

00:20:30.578 --> 00:20:33.250
while they do your testing.

00:20:33.250 --> 00:20:36.145
If you can encourage your
players to talk to the game

00:20:36.145 --> 00:20:38.300
or to talk out loud
while they play,

00:20:38.300 --> 00:20:42.680
that's the greatest thing ever.

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:44.920
The best people I've
ever heard play games

00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:50.120
are middle schoolers because
they connect their brain

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:52.660
straight to their mouth
without any filter,

00:20:52.660 --> 00:20:53.685
and they're just there.

00:20:53.685 --> 00:20:55.310
They're telling you
what they're doing.

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:56.490
They're telling you
why they're doing it.

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:58.948
They're telling you why this
particular aspect of your game

00:20:58.948 --> 00:21:01.590
is the worst thing ever, or
why this particular aspect

00:21:01.590 --> 00:21:04.340
of your game is the
greatest thing ever.

00:21:04.340 --> 00:21:06.970
And you can just sit
there and listen to them

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:08.920
and you know why
they're doing things.

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:10.165
Adults are a lot quieter.

00:21:10.165 --> 00:21:12.540
We often don't want to explain
why we're doing something.

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:15.210
Often it's because we don't
know we're supposed to be doing.

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:17.420
And we don't want to admit that
I don't know what I'm doing.

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:19.378
I'm just going to poke
stuff until I figure out

00:21:19.378 --> 00:21:21.580
what's going on.

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:23.680
So that's where you
want to watch people.

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:27.190
And if you really need
to, you can lead and say,

00:21:27.190 --> 00:21:29.160
why did you do that thing?

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:32.432
Or even better, what
are you thinking?

00:21:32.432 --> 00:21:34.140
People will often
answer those questions.

00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:35.889
But you really want
to keep those prodding

00:21:35.889 --> 00:21:37.550
questions neutral.

00:21:37.550 --> 00:21:40.140
Don't say, why did you
do that crazy thing?

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:43.160
Or, what are you
looking for back there?

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:44.990
But just, what are you thinking?

00:21:44.990 --> 00:21:47.240
What are you doing?

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:50.090
What's your plan?

00:21:50.090 --> 00:21:51.650
That sort of thing.

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:53.670
Once you've got
your data the team

00:21:53.670 --> 00:21:57.470
can review it together to notice
trends, spot common problems,

00:21:57.470 --> 00:21:58.290
and so on.

00:21:58.290 --> 00:22:01.950
And that's where the things
that four or five or a majority

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:05.555
of your testers did or
said or ran into, that's

00:22:05.555 --> 00:22:07.430
what you're going to be
pulling out and using

00:22:07.430 --> 00:22:10.030
to think about how you're
going to fix those problems.

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:12.380
Or if you noticed a trend
that you hadn't noticed before

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:14.250
that people were really
liking an aspect of your game

00:22:14.250 --> 00:22:15.990
you haven't thought
about, it's something

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:18.300
you can work on magnifying
so that you can share it

00:22:18.300 --> 00:22:18.900
with everyone.

00:22:22.340 --> 00:22:26.230
So for those of you who fell
asleep while I was talking,

00:22:26.230 --> 00:22:28.860
the too long didn't
read version really

00:22:28.860 --> 00:22:32.250
is who are you testing with,
because your audience will

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:33.920
affect your data.

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:35.970
What are you testing with?

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:38.770
The state of your game
will affect your data.

00:22:38.770 --> 00:22:41.952
That shouldn't stop you from
testing with early builds,

00:22:41.952 --> 00:22:44.160
but it does mean you need
to adjust your expectations

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:46.450
and make sure your players
are ready to play with it.

00:22:49.370 --> 00:22:52.380
And finally, why
are you testing?

00:22:52.380 --> 00:22:54.490
Only you can answer
that question.

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:57.284
We can give you a lot of
reasons or suggestions,

00:22:57.284 --> 00:22:58.700
but if you're
running a focus test

00:22:58.700 --> 00:23:02.210
it really needs to be because
you're looking for data

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:05.110
that your team intends to use.

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:07.240
And you can always use
data to support your game.

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:07.950
You really can.

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:10.460
Even if you don't realize
that you need it, you do.

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:15.420
And I keep saying
"and gather data."

00:23:15.420 --> 00:23:16.990
And I talked about observations.

00:23:16.990 --> 00:23:19.080
I talked about surveys.

00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:23.300
I talked about interviews,
which are our three major tools

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:28.264
unless you are going to go to
all the work of videotaping

00:23:28.264 --> 00:23:29.930
and audio recording
and getting releases

00:23:29.930 --> 00:23:32.030
from your testers, which
I really don't recommend.

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:34.550
That's more work than
you should be doing.

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:36.860
But the three major tools
really are observing people

00:23:36.860 --> 00:23:39.730
and taking notes, asking them
a standard set of questions

00:23:39.730 --> 00:23:42.700
afterwards-- either on
paper or in person--

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:45.200
and thinking about
what kind of data

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:50.260
you can gather best with
each of those methods.

00:23:50.260 --> 00:23:52.650
If you have 20 different
levels you want someone

00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:55.369
to rate at a one to five as
to whether it's good or not,

00:23:55.369 --> 00:23:57.035
you should just give
them piece of paper

00:23:57.035 --> 00:23:58.576
and when they finish
each level, they

00:23:58.576 --> 00:24:01.500
can check a number
between one and five.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.566
If you want to see how
long it takes someone

00:24:03.566 --> 00:24:05.440
to get started playing
the game, you probably

00:24:05.440 --> 00:24:07.700
just want to watch
them with a timer.

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:10.140
How long does it take them
to get from that first screen

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:14.820
to getting into the game?

00:24:14.820 --> 00:24:17.287
And finally, if you want to
get a general impression,

00:24:17.287 --> 00:24:19.370
sometimes talking to people
helps bring out things

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:20.411
that you didn't think of.

00:24:20.411 --> 00:24:22.260
You can get some
insights you wouldn't

00:24:22.260 --> 00:24:24.970
have thought to ask for
by talking with people.

00:24:24.970 --> 00:24:27.219
But be a little careful
talking with people,

00:24:27.219 --> 00:24:28.760
because people don't
want to tell you

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:30.710
bad things to your face.

00:24:30.710 --> 00:24:33.640
They'd rather write the bad
things down on a piece of paper

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:35.514
where they don't have
to admit that they said

00:24:35.514 --> 00:24:36.970
bad things about this game.

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:39.050
That covers less for
middle school students,

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:42.260
as I mentioned earlier.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:44.450
But most people
don't really want

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:46.860
to say mean things
to the person who

00:24:46.860 --> 00:24:50.040
made the game, because we don't
want to make people feel bad.

00:24:50.040 --> 00:24:51.710
So you need to
balance that out when

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:53.460
you're asking people
questions about well,

00:24:53.460 --> 00:24:55.810
how did you like the game?

00:24:55.810 --> 00:24:58.171
The answer is usually,
oh, it's great.

00:24:58.171 --> 00:24:58.670
Yeah.

