and there's over 120
of them in our game.

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:41.989
So even though each
game is session based--

00:34:41.989 --> 00:34:44.667
you don't level up your
character necessarily

00:34:44.667 --> 00:34:46.250
over the lifetime
of playing the game,

00:34:46.250 --> 00:34:49.159
each session is a new session--
there's lots of different ways

00:34:49.159 --> 00:34:51.150
to play because we have lots
of different characters, which

00:34:51.150 --> 00:34:52.358
I'll talk to in a little bit.

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:56.750
So one of things
that I talked about

00:34:56.750 --> 00:34:59.290
is it's really hard to
be player-focused if you

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:01.330
don't talk to your players.

00:35:01.330 --> 00:35:03.000
And one of things at
Riot is that we all

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:03.990
play League of Legends.

00:35:03.990 --> 00:35:05.700
In fact, some of
us play it a lot.

00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:07.480
Some of us play a lot at work.

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:09.640
But just because you
play your own game

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:12.250
doesn't mean that you
actually know what it's

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:13.530
like for all of your players.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:16.140
And using MIT students
is a great example.

00:35:16.140 --> 00:35:17.970
If you guys just play
with MIT students,

00:35:17.970 --> 00:35:20.130
you might not know what
it's like for people

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:22.380
in other countries, for example.

00:35:22.380 --> 00:35:24.130
So one of things we
try to do is make sure

00:35:24.130 --> 00:35:25.860
that we understand
our players broadly

00:35:25.860 --> 00:35:27.390
and know that we
are our players,

00:35:27.390 --> 00:35:31.510
but we are a small
sub-segment of our players.

00:35:31.510 --> 00:35:33.300
The way we use
research is it equips

00:35:33.300 --> 00:35:36.090
us to understand player beliefs,
their needs, their desires,

00:35:36.090 --> 00:35:37.590
and their relationship
with the game

00:35:37.590 --> 00:35:39.870
and with other
people in the game.

00:35:39.870 --> 00:35:43.170
And what this allows us to
do is design experiences.

00:35:43.170 --> 00:35:46.764
So there's specific
experiences, interactions

00:35:46.764 --> 00:35:47.930
that we're hoping to design.

00:35:47.930 --> 00:35:49.890
So in general when we're
creating a feature,

00:35:49.890 --> 00:35:52.550
we have a set of goals that
we're trying to achieve.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:55.590
And what we want to do is
we want to help designers.

00:35:55.590 --> 00:35:58.110
developers, QA,
artists, we want to help

00:35:58.110 --> 00:35:59.489
them achieve these goals.

00:35:59.489 --> 00:36:02.030
So we want to know exactly what
they're trying to do and then

00:36:02.030 --> 00:36:04.240
get them feedback on how
well those goals are being

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:06.360
communicated to players,
how well they're actually

00:36:06.360 --> 00:36:08.110
able to interact with
those, and then what

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:11.036
their reception is as a result.

00:36:11.036 --> 00:36:12.660
So the way I'm going
to break this down

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:14.850
is play tests and user
labs, which is essentially

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:16.516
the way we were talking
about it before,

00:36:16.516 --> 00:36:19.740
is play tests and user tests.

00:36:19.740 --> 00:36:23.500
So play test is the backbone
of creating your game.

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:25.900
It's really, really
difficult to create a game

00:36:25.900 --> 00:36:27.040
without play testing it.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:29.540
So I'm glad that's really part
of how you guys are designing

00:36:29.540 --> 00:36:30.410
your games.

00:36:30.410 --> 00:36:32.820
And play tests basically
allow us to quickly gather

00:36:32.820 --> 00:36:35.140
information about
a game or a feature

00:36:35.140 --> 00:36:36.750
to see how it's working.

00:36:36.750 --> 00:36:39.036
And typically, this
is done with resources

00:36:39.036 --> 00:36:40.160
that are readily available.

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:43.470
So people in your dorms, people
in your class, or at Riot,

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:47.212
we often do it with other
Rioters, and even on the team.

00:36:47.212 --> 00:36:49.170
And some of the benefits
we can get out of this

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:51.060
is we can identify
technical issues.

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:53.067
Now, Sara talked
about a specific type

00:36:53.067 --> 00:36:55.150
of this, which is quality
assurance testing, which

00:36:55.150 --> 00:36:56.446
is less what I'm talking about.

00:36:56.446 --> 00:36:58.320
I'm more talking about
testing with your team

00:36:58.320 --> 00:37:00.710
to just quickly identify
technical issues that

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:02.722
might prevent you from
playing that game.

00:37:02.722 --> 00:37:04.430
You can also look at
things like balance.

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:06.710
So in a competitive game
like League of Legends,

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:08.550
you play against other players.

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:11.160
And if one type of character
is really overpowered

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:13.950
or has a significant advantage
over another type of character,

00:37:13.950 --> 00:37:16.140
we can quickly identify
that through play testing.

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:18.850
So for instance, our designers
have two play tests a day

00:37:18.850 --> 00:37:20.970
where they test their
in-progress champions

00:37:20.970 --> 00:37:23.150
to see if there's anything
basically game breaking

00:37:23.150 --> 00:37:25.970
like that that they can quickly
identify and iterate on.

00:37:25.970 --> 00:37:27.489
We can also look
at things for fun.

00:37:27.489 --> 00:37:29.030
I mean, this is the
most obvious one.

00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:31.196
But it's really important
when you're making a game,

00:37:31.196 --> 00:37:33.840
if the game is supposed to be
fun, that it is actually fun.

00:37:33.840 --> 00:37:36.400
And in our case, we do
want to have a fun game.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:39.250
So we have a whole group
of designers and developers

00:37:39.250 --> 00:37:41.300
that have a team which
is known as the play team

00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:43.190
and they make
temporary game modes.

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:45.010
So I don't know if
anybody played recently,

00:37:45.010 --> 00:37:47.430
but we had a big in-game
event called Shurima,

00:37:47.430 --> 00:37:49.410
and we had this game
mode called Ascension.

00:37:49.410 --> 00:37:50.868
And when they were
developing that,

00:37:50.868 --> 00:37:54.070
they were often several times
a day-- many, many times a day,

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:56.296
in some cases--
testing every iteration

00:37:56.296 --> 00:37:58.170
that they made to that
game mode to make sure

00:37:58.170 --> 00:37:59.242
that it was actually fun.

00:37:59.242 --> 00:38:00.700
And a lot of times
what you'll find

00:38:00.700 --> 00:38:03.490
is that your game isn't
necessarily fun sometimes.

00:38:03.490 --> 00:38:05.730
And that's OK, because each
time you make a change,

00:38:05.730 --> 00:38:07.410
you're getting closer
to that fun experience.

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:09.640
One day, you'll be playing
your game and like, oh my gosh,

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:10.570
it's actually fun now.

00:38:10.570 --> 00:38:11.153
This is great.

00:38:11.153 --> 00:38:11.800
Let's do this.

00:38:11.800 --> 00:38:14.641
So it's a really good
way to get that feedback.

00:38:14.641 --> 00:38:16.890
And another specific area
that we're looking for a lot

00:38:16.890 --> 00:38:18.305
when we play test is clarity.

00:38:18.305 --> 00:38:19.680
And clarity is a
word that we use

00:38:19.680 --> 00:38:22.500
to mean basically how
clear is the information--

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:25.590
either the visual information
or the mechanical information--

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:27.820
how well is that being
communicated to players?

00:38:27.820 --> 00:38:29.680
So this could be
something like with UI,

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:31.430
if you just have a
picture and you show it

00:38:31.430 --> 00:38:34.850
to players or to your
dorm-mates, your classmates,

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:38.040
how easily are they able to
identify what a button means?

00:38:38.040 --> 00:38:40.475
Or which things are
clickable and not clickable.

00:38:40.475 --> 00:38:42.350
Those things are all
really, really important

00:38:42.350 --> 00:38:44.150
in a game like
ours where we have

00:38:44.150 --> 00:38:46.935
five people on a team, 10
people on the map, each

00:38:46.935 --> 00:38:49.060
with their own set of
abilities and visual effects.

00:38:49.060 --> 00:38:50.810
And there could be a
lot of visual clutter

00:38:50.810 --> 00:38:53.079
if we didn't think about
this type of thing.

00:38:53.079 --> 00:38:55.620
And then the way we typically
get these, at least at Riot, is

00:38:55.620 --> 00:38:56.720
like I said, team tests.

00:38:56.720 --> 00:38:59.260
That's the example I used with
the designers and the play

00:38:59.260 --> 00:38:59.761
team.

00:38:59.761 --> 00:39:01.343
They're just playing
within their team

00:39:01.343 --> 00:39:03.680
frequently to make sure that
they can quickly and easily

00:39:03.680 --> 00:39:05.300
give each other feedback.

00:39:05.300 --> 00:39:06.960
Quality assurance
test is another type

00:39:06.960 --> 00:39:09.000
that's a very specific
implementation of this,

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:10.420
which Sara spoke to.

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:12.456
And in house "guerrilla
tests"-- and I always

00:39:12.456 --> 00:39:14.330
have to be careful how
I say "guerrilla," not

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:15.960
"gorilla." "Guerrilla."

00:39:15.960 --> 00:39:17.950
This is when we bring
other Rioters who

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:20.670
aren't part of a team who
maybe haven't had exposure

00:39:20.670 --> 00:39:22.090
to that particular feature.

00:39:22.090 --> 00:39:23.790
This is particularly
useful for things

00:39:23.790 --> 00:39:27.400
like clarity or usability tests,
because we don't necessarily

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:30.590
need to have that perception
or that sentiment that

00:39:30.590 --> 00:39:32.450
is really unique to players.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:34.500
What we need here
instead is just see, hey,

00:39:34.500 --> 00:39:37.637
how easily is this usable for
a reasonably tech savvy person?

00:39:37.637 --> 00:39:40.220
But even then, of course, there
are some cultural differences.

00:39:40.220 --> 00:39:41.760
There's some
hardware differences.

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:44.510
So it's a first phase when you
do them as guerrilla testing.

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:46.635
And you always want to make
sure that you follow up

00:39:46.635 --> 00:39:49.800
with real players
after the fact.

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:52.280
So user labs, this is
what I really focus in.

00:39:52.280 --> 00:39:54.154
So I use a lot of
different methods at Riot,

00:39:54.154 --> 00:39:55.570
but one of the key
ways that we're

00:39:55.570 --> 00:39:58.500
able to get player feedback
is by bringing players

00:39:58.500 --> 00:40:00.577
to Riot to have
them play the game.

00:40:00.577 --> 00:40:02.160
So this is a way to
help us understand

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:06.430
how real players will
actually approach a feature.

00:40:06.430 --> 00:40:09.650
What we get out of this is
really, really important.

00:40:09.650 --> 00:40:11.130
We get reception and interest.

00:40:11.130 --> 00:40:13.640
Like, how stoked are players
going to be about something,

00:40:13.640 --> 00:40:16.420
or what we call the
table flip reaction.

00:40:16.420 --> 00:40:18.422
Which is like, we're
working on an update

00:40:18.422 --> 00:40:19.630
to Summoner's Rift right now.

00:40:19.630 --> 00:40:20.736
And it was early on.

00:40:20.736 --> 00:40:22.360
It was really important
for us to know,

00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:23.770
were players going
to be really upset

00:40:23.770 --> 00:40:26.230
that we were changing something
that's so key to the game.

00:40:26.230 --> 00:40:27.920
So we made sure to
loop them on very early

00:40:27.920 --> 00:40:30.420
in on the process to see how
they were responding to changes

00:40:30.420 --> 00:40:31.700
we were going to make.

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:34.220
We also look for things like
usage patterns and errors.

00:40:34.220 --> 00:40:35.595
And this is
important that we get

00:40:35.595 --> 00:40:37.740
a broad swath of
different types of players

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.750
to look at this type
of thing, especially

00:40:39.750 --> 00:40:42.070
with things like we
just updated the client.

00:40:42.070 --> 00:40:44.300
Making sure that the changes
we made to the interface

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:46.180
weren't going to
confuse players--

00:40:46.180 --> 00:40:48.810
experienced players who
were used to our old version

00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:50.280
and new players
who would be coming

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:51.770
into our game for
the first time.

00:40:51.770 --> 00:40:54.100
We also look at
needs and desires.

00:40:54.100 --> 00:40:58.350
And this is not like Maslov's--
Maslow's hierarchy of needs.

00:40:58.350 --> 00:41:00.750
It's more like, what are
things that players really

00:41:00.750 --> 00:41:02.840
want from our game?

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:05.870
And understanding that
can be difficult sometimes

00:41:05.870 --> 00:41:07.950
because, like I said,
we all play our game.

00:41:07.950 --> 00:41:09.700
We're very entrenched
in this experience.

00:41:09.700 --> 00:41:11.650
We have our own
experience in the game

00:41:11.650 --> 00:41:13.560
that we feel very
strongly about.

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:15.706
But understanding that
other players might

00:41:15.706 --> 00:41:17.080
have different
needs and desires,

00:41:17.080 --> 00:41:18.663
and understanding
what proportion that

00:41:18.663 --> 00:41:20.980
represents within our
broader player base,

00:41:20.980 --> 00:41:23.430
these are really important
things to understand.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:25.320
How we get this is a
lot of different ways

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:26.790
that I'm actually going
to go into in a little bit

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:27.660
more detail.

00:41:27.660 --> 00:41:30.147
And each one has a
specific application,

00:41:30.147 --> 00:41:31.730
but there are a few
that we use pretty

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:33.230
much in every user
lab, which I'm

00:41:33.230 --> 00:41:35.202
going to go through right now.

00:41:35.202 --> 00:41:37.160
So the first is something
we just talked about,

00:41:37.160 --> 00:41:38.455
which is just observation.

00:41:38.455 --> 00:41:41.080
And I bring this up because it's
something that anybody can do.

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:44.000
You don't need a dedicated
researcher like myself.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.210
You guys should and
will be doing this.

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:48.200
And so in this
case, I have Chris,

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:50.860
who is a developer at Riot,
sitting in for a player.

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:53.550
And I have [? Jisan, ?] who
is another researcher at Riot,

00:41:53.550 --> 00:41:56.310
sitting over his shoulder
watching him play.

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.570
In our case, we typically
just have one researcher

00:41:58.570 --> 00:42:00.400
in the room both
taking the notes

00:42:00.400 --> 00:42:02.140
and doing the
observation, just because

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:03.690
of resource limitations.

00:42:03.690 --> 00:42:06.420
And because we've done this a
lot and it's our full time job.

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:09.220
So in this case,
[? Jisan ?] is watching

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:11.012
Chris interact with the client.

00:42:11.012 --> 00:42:13.470
And you can see in his hand,
he's actually got the script--

00:42:13.470 --> 00:42:15.670
or what we call
protocol-- in his hands

00:42:15.670 --> 00:42:18.160
so he can remember what things
he should be looking for,

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:19.392
what things he wants to say.

00:42:19.392 --> 00:42:21.850
In this case, we don't generally
try to use it as a script.

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:24.082
We try to use it as
a memory refresher.

00:42:24.082 --> 00:42:26.290
That way, players can feel
really comfortable with us

00:42:26.290 --> 00:42:27.873
and feel like they
have a relationship

00:42:27.873 --> 00:42:30.692
and can have a
comfortable conversation.

00:42:30.692 --> 00:42:32.650
One of the ways we achieve
this is through what

00:42:32.650 --> 00:42:34.945
we call the Think Aloud
protocol, which is what Sara

00:42:34.945 --> 00:42:36.350
was referencing,
which is basically we

00:42:36.350 --> 00:42:38.350
try to make sure that
they have this direct link

00:42:38.350 --> 00:42:39.740
from their mind to their mouth.

00:42:39.740 --> 00:42:41.530
And there's a couple
ways to achieve this

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:43.590
that I'll speak to,
but the goal of this

00:42:43.590 --> 00:42:46.150
is we want to know exactly
what the game is communicating

00:42:46.150 --> 00:42:48.950
to players, and then how
players are processing that

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:50.492
and creating an internal model.

00:42:50.492 --> 00:42:51.950
And the best way
to do that is just

00:42:51.950 --> 00:42:53.610
to step back and
let them tell you

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:55.210
exactly what they're seeing.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:57.270
And if you aren't quite
sure what they're seeing,

00:42:57.270 --> 00:42:59.542
then you can follow up, which
I'll get to in a second.

00:42:59.542 --> 00:43:02.000
So here's an example of a player
who's seeing our character

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.210
Lucian, who is a
champion who was released

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:05.810
fairly recently in the game.

00:43:05.810 --> 00:43:08.190
She's seeing him before
he had been released

00:43:08.190 --> 00:43:09.940
in a work in progress
state and giving us

00:43:09.940 --> 00:43:12.374
feedback on what she sees.

00:43:12.374 --> 00:43:13.040
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:17.140
-I can see that he walks
faster than the normal--

00:43:17.140 --> 00:43:18.012
[END PLAYBACK]

00:43:18.012 --> 00:43:21.002
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: Sorry, we
forgot to plug in the audio.

00:43:21.002 --> 00:43:22.710
I think you guys could
hear it all right.

00:43:26.066 --> 00:43:26.566
All right.

00:43:26.566 --> 00:43:27.048
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:27.048 --> 00:43:27.530
-[INAUDIBLE].

00:43:27.530 --> 00:43:28.488
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: Oops.

00:43:31.386 --> 00:43:36.832
-I can see that he walks faster
than the normal character

00:43:36.832 --> 00:43:41.188
would, but his animation
doesn't make it seem so.

00:43:41.188 --> 00:43:44.576
It seems like he takes
a really big stride,

00:43:44.576 --> 00:43:49.076
but I was imagining him
to walk really fast.

00:43:49.076 --> 00:43:51.556
But it seems like it
looks like that way.

00:43:51.556 --> 00:43:52.140
[END PLAYBACK]

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:53.764
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: So
this is an example

00:43:53.764 --> 00:43:56.210
where the player has just
brought this up to us that she

00:43:56.210 --> 00:43:58.650
expected him to move one
way, and he's actually

00:43:58.650 --> 00:44:00.349
operating in a different way.

00:44:00.349 --> 00:44:02.140
You can think of this
is as like, basically

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:03.750
a violation of
expectations, which

00:44:03.750 --> 00:44:07.010
is often what we're looking for
especially with our characters.

00:44:07.010 --> 00:44:09.580
Does what you see and what you
hear about a champion match

00:44:09.580 --> 00:44:11.340
with how they actually play?

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:13.540
So one way you can do this
is to just let them talk.

00:44:13.540 --> 00:44:17.090
And it is really important
not to be giving feedback on

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:19.150
whether or not you
think they're correct,

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:20.840
especially if they
do have a question.

00:44:20.840 --> 00:44:23.300
It's also really important
not to be judgmental, right?

00:44:23.300 --> 00:44:24.895
So the way you phrase
your questions,

00:44:24.895 --> 00:44:26.770
even if you aren't
actually being judgmental,

00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:29.620
sometimes players might think
that you're judging them.

00:44:29.620 --> 00:44:32.120
So one of the contexts
we give players upfront

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:33.942
is always for us,
since we actually

00:44:33.942 --> 00:44:36.400
didn't work on the game or the
feature that they're seeing,

00:44:36.400 --> 00:44:38.540
we can say, we
didn't work on this.

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:40.920
It's really important that
you give us honest feedback.

00:44:40.920 --> 00:44:42.669
I'm not going to go
home and cry at night,

00:44:42.669 --> 00:44:44.894
so I want you to give me
totally honest feedback.

00:44:44.894 --> 00:44:46.810
And we also let them
know that sometimes we're

00:44:46.810 --> 00:44:49.060
going to ask them questions,
and we're asking it

00:44:49.060 --> 00:44:50.670
so that we can
understand what they're

00:44:50.670 --> 00:44:51.920
thinking because
that's what we're

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:53.086
interested in understanding.

00:44:53.086 --> 00:44:54.480
We're not asking
it because there

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:56.966
is a right or wrong answer.

00:44:56.966 --> 00:44:58.590
So one of the ways
that makes it easier

00:44:58.590 --> 00:45:00.910
to make sure that
we understand what

00:45:00.910 --> 00:45:02.455
their mental model
of the game is

00:45:02.455 --> 00:45:04.600
is a follow-up with
some probing questions.

00:45:04.600 --> 00:45:06.330
So the player in
the previous example

00:45:06.330 --> 00:45:08.220
was pretty clear about
what she was seeing

00:45:08.220 --> 00:45:10.066
and why it violated
her expectations,

00:45:10.066 --> 00:45:11.690
but sometimes players
don't necessarily

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:14.110
know why it doesn't actually
fit what they expected.

00:45:14.110 --> 00:45:16.110
Or they might know that
something's frustrating,

00:45:16.110 --> 00:45:18.340
but they're not necessarily
giving you the answer why.

00:45:18.340 --> 00:45:19.560
So one of the ways
you can follow it up

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:21.170
is either with probing
questions, which

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:23.640
you ask in the moment, or you
can follow up with interviews

00:45:23.640 --> 00:45:24.500
after the fact.

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:26.499
So here's an example of
[? Jisan ?] following up

00:45:26.499 --> 00:45:29.214
with a player who just saw
Lucian for the first time.

00:45:29.214 --> 00:45:29.880
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:45:29.880 --> 00:45:32.130
-How was that play [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:32.130 --> 00:45:33.250
-I thought it was fun.

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:35.896
I thought it was
[? different. ?]

00:45:35.896 --> 00:45:38.782
-What makes it fun and
something different about it?

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:47.914
-So he, I guess, normal
[INAUDIBLE] skills,

00:45:47.914 --> 00:45:49.122
just increased the intensity.

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:55.290
A lot of his skills based off
of move speed and [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:55.290 --> 00:45:58.720
speed, and I guess he
feels [? confident. ?]

00:45:58.720 --> 00:45:59.454
[END PLAYBACK]

00:45:59.454 --> 00:46:01.120
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: So
this is an example.

00:46:01.120 --> 00:46:02.578
A lot of times
you'll find this, is

00:46:02.578 --> 00:46:04.530
that when you ask
that initial question,

00:46:04.530 --> 00:46:06.260
you get a short response.

00:46:06.260 --> 00:46:09.010
And what we're always trying
to do as researchers is invite

00:46:09.010 --> 00:46:12.260
a conversation where they're
just really comfortable telling

00:46:12.260 --> 00:46:14.855
us exactly what they feel and
giving us a lot of detail.

00:46:14.855 --> 00:46:17.230
So in the first question, he
asked a really broad opening

00:46:17.230 --> 00:46:19.200
question, which
was "how was that?"

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:20.992
He didn't even ask,
"how did that feel,"

00:46:20.992 --> 00:46:22.700
which might lead in
a certain direction--

00:46:22.700 --> 00:46:24.930
although that would be an
appropriate question as well.

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:26.400
He left it wide
open for the player

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:28.502
to take us where they
wanted to talk about it.

00:46:28.502 --> 00:46:29.960
So the player
mentioned that it was

00:46:29.960 --> 00:46:31.500
fun and something different.

00:46:31.500 --> 00:46:33.430
So [? Jisan ?] wanted
to get more depth

00:46:33.430 --> 00:46:35.940
into what does that actually
mean, because that alone

00:46:35.940 --> 00:46:37.560
doesn't give us
enough direction to be

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:40.020
able to provide to our
designers to say what was good,

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:41.130
what was working.

00:46:41.130 --> 00:46:44.300
So he mirrored exactly what
the player said back at him.

00:46:44.300 --> 00:46:46.600
He said, oh, what
was fun and what

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.540
was the thing that
made it feel different?

00:46:48.540 --> 00:46:50.540
And then the player, that
way we're not actually

00:46:50.540 --> 00:46:52.130
putting our own
spin on interpreting

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:54.746
what we think they're saying is
fun or maybe what's different.

00:46:54.746 --> 00:46:56.120
We're just mirroring
exactly back

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:59.075
what they said so that they
can give us more detail.

00:46:59.075 --> 00:47:00.450
You have to be
careful with that,

00:47:00.450 --> 00:47:02.320
because you also don't want
to sound cold and clinical

00:47:02.320 --> 00:47:04.770
like you're sitting in an
office somewhere writing down

00:47:04.770 --> 00:47:06.495
everything they say,
which you will be.

00:47:06.495 --> 00:47:09.371
You want to make it feel like
it's a natural conversation.

00:47:09.371 --> 00:47:10.870
So we're really
lucky because we get

00:47:10.870 --> 00:47:12.440
to work with League
of Legends players

00:47:12.440 --> 00:47:14.390
so we already have a
connection built up with them

00:47:14.390 --> 00:47:16.973
where we can talk about it, but
it's really important that you

00:47:16.973 --> 00:47:19.290
make that as hey, I want
to know what you think.

00:47:19.290 --> 00:47:20.374
You're really valuable.

00:47:20.374 --> 00:47:22.040
Let's just have a
conversation about it.

00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:25.750
And it can be really
challenging sometimes.

00:47:25.750 --> 00:47:27.530
So this is one that
you guys are already

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:30.120
pretty familiar with,
too, is part of interviews

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:33.259
that I've clumped in here is
basically the questionnaire.

00:47:33.259 --> 00:47:34.800
Sara gave you guys
some great context

00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:36.242
about when this might be useful.

00:47:36.242 --> 00:47:37.700
Here's an example
of when we use it

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:39.690
in League of Legends research.

00:47:39.690 --> 00:47:41.830
So this is an example
with Azir, who

00:47:41.830 --> 00:47:44.536
is a character who just came
out in League of Legends.

00:47:44.536 --> 00:47:46.160
This is actually from
quite a long time

00:47:46.160 --> 00:47:47.991
ago when he was in
the concept phase.

00:47:47.991 --> 00:47:49.490
And this is something
we do actually

00:47:49.490 --> 00:47:52.031
with most of our concepts, is
we put them in front of players

00:47:52.031 --> 00:47:54.140
before they go into
development to see, hey,

00:47:54.140 --> 00:47:55.170
is this something
that feels like it

00:47:55.170 --> 00:47:56.794
fits in the world of
League of Legends?

00:47:56.794 --> 00:47:58.940
Is it clear where maybe
the source of power is?

00:47:58.940 --> 00:48:01.148
And does this look like a
champion you would actually

00:48:01.148 --> 00:48:01.760
want to play?

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:04.446
Now, we don't use data to
drive decisions at Riot.

00:48:04.446 --> 00:48:05.820
I want to make
that really clear.

00:48:05.820 --> 00:48:06.810
We use it to inform.

00:48:06.810 --> 00:48:08.440
So just because something
wasn't resonating

00:48:08.440 --> 00:48:09.815
with players in
our labs wouldn't

00:48:09.815 --> 00:48:11.610
mean that we would
cancel a character.

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:13.220
It's just a way for
us to get feedback

00:48:13.220 --> 00:48:15.480
for our designers who
already have their experience

00:48:15.480 --> 00:48:18.320
and the experience
testing with other Rioters

00:48:18.320 --> 00:48:20.815
to help them make
informed decisions.

00:48:20.815 --> 00:48:22.940
So what's useful about a
questionnaire in this case

00:48:22.940 --> 00:48:26.200
is that we can compare
across champions over time

00:48:26.200 --> 00:48:28.270
and across different
roles or positions

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:32.334
and see what is resonating
and what does good look like.

00:48:32.334 --> 00:48:34.000
We also use this as
a jumping off point.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:35.260
So we start with
a questionnaire,

00:48:35.260 --> 00:48:37.545
and then we go into a more
detailed interview about it

00:48:37.545 --> 00:48:39.670
to make sure that we're
getting enough detail to be

00:48:39.670 --> 00:48:41.836
able to provide useful
information to the designers.

00:48:44.140 --> 00:48:46.090
So you guys are also
probably pretty familiar

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:48.290
with the idea of
experiments in general.

00:48:48.290 --> 00:48:51.550
But part of research testing
can be devising experiments.

00:48:51.550 --> 00:48:54.420
So we often hire people
from psychology backgrounds

00:48:54.420 --> 00:48:56.010
or research
backgrounds in academia

00:48:56.010 --> 00:48:58.580
because they have experience
setting up experiments.

00:48:58.580 --> 00:49:00.100
So this is like the classic one.

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:01.390
I don't know if you guys
have already covered

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:02.780
this, the Engelbart experiment.

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:03.450
OK.

00:49:03.450 --> 00:49:06.020
So this is foundational
human computer interaction.

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:08.430
It's one of the
most cited studies.

00:49:08.430 --> 00:49:11.290
And it's English, Engerlbart,
and Berman basically

00:49:11.290 --> 00:49:14.450
were looking for a
way to improve a way

00:49:14.450 --> 00:49:17.310
to interact with a screen
or text manipulation.

00:49:17.310 --> 00:49:18.997
And what they
proposed was something

00:49:18.997 --> 00:49:20.830
that was radical and
was called the "mouse."

00:49:20.830 --> 00:49:22.714
Maybe you've heard of it.

00:49:22.714 --> 00:49:24.130
So that thing in
the right, I know

00:49:24.130 --> 00:49:25.960
it's not a really
clear photo, but that

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:28.842
is one of the first early
prototypes of a mouse.

00:49:28.842 --> 00:49:30.800
And what they wanted to
do is they want to see,

00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:33.160
is this better than some
of these other interactions

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:35.380
out there.

00:49:35.380 --> 00:49:38.380
Qualitative experience alone
might not be a very strong way

00:49:38.380 --> 00:49:40.330
to prove it in this
case, especially when you

00:49:40.330 --> 00:49:43.160
can collect quantitative
data to back it up.

00:49:43.160 --> 00:49:46.400
So what they did is
they used the time

00:49:46.400 --> 00:49:48.860
that it took to complete a
task, a very specific task that

00:49:48.860 --> 00:49:51.235
was given across all these
different ways of manipulating

00:49:51.235 --> 00:49:52.040
text.

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:55.305
And they saw how many errors
the user made in this case.

00:49:55.305 --> 00:49:57.180
So you can see that the
mouse did pretty well

00:49:57.180 --> 00:49:58.221
in terms of time overall.

00:49:58.221 --> 00:50:00.430
It didn't take the
participants very long

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:02.180
to be able to complete the task.

00:50:02.180 --> 00:50:03.760
But it had very
few errors, which

00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:06.940
made it overall the best
out of these different ways

00:50:06.940 --> 00:50:07.740
to select text.

00:50:07.740 --> 00:50:09.656
And you can see some of
the other ones on here

00:50:09.656 --> 00:50:13.080
were things like knee control,
joystick, a graphicon, which

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:17.170
is like an arc drawer, a
light pen, and a joystick.

00:50:17.170 --> 00:50:19.020
And all of these were
ways that we could

00:50:19.020 --> 00:50:21.050
have gone instead of the mouse.

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:22.540
But based on some
of this research,

00:50:22.540 --> 00:50:24.147
they were able to
improve their design

00:50:24.147 --> 00:50:25.980
and now you can see I'm
using one right now.

00:50:29.630 --> 00:50:32.124
And as part of the experimental
approach, I broke it out,

00:50:32.124 --> 00:50:33.540
but there's a
specific way you can

00:50:33.540 --> 00:50:36.020
look at it, which is using
physiological techniques.

00:50:36.020 --> 00:50:38.720
And there are many, and I'm
just going to cover two.

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:41.270
And typically, these are
used for very specific types

00:50:41.270 --> 00:50:42.020
of research.

00:50:42.020 --> 00:50:43.000
They're very exciting.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.666
So oftentimes, you'll see people
want to use them on everything.

00:50:45.666 --> 00:50:49.020
But they're very particularly
useful for certain cases.

00:50:49.020 --> 00:50:52.240
So this is an example of eye
tracking, which is basically

00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:54.140
fundamentally, we
put a camera up

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:56.432
that's able to specially
track where eye movements are.

00:50:56.432 --> 00:50:58.931
And there are more sophisticated
ways you can look at this--

00:50:58.931 --> 00:51:00.692
and I'm sure a bunch
of researchers at MIT

00:51:00.692 --> 00:51:02.150
could tell you a
lot more about it.

00:51:02.150 --> 00:51:03.510
But in this case, it
was pretty simple.

00:51:03.510 --> 00:51:05.551
We were just looking at
where people were looking

00:51:05.551 --> 00:51:08.330
on the screen and how
often and how long

00:51:08.330 --> 00:51:09.430
they were looking there.

00:51:09.430 --> 00:51:11.120
So you can see the
red parts of the map

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:14.870
here are the parts where there
are more intense gazes or more

00:51:14.870 --> 00:51:16.520
gazes overall.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:18.112
So unsurprisingly
to probably most

00:51:18.112 --> 00:51:19.820
of the League of
Legends players in here,

00:51:19.820 --> 00:51:21.840
or you guys as
gamers in general,

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:24.250
the mini map has a lot of gaze.

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:27.250
The bottom part, which is where
the abilities are displayed,

00:51:27.250 --> 00:51:28.510
also has a lot of gaze.

00:51:28.510 --> 00:51:30.010
That has a lot of
information that's

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:32.601
really relevant to players
like the cool down timer,

00:51:32.601 --> 00:51:34.850
basically when the ability
is going to be ready again.

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:37.183
And the center of the screen
is where most of the action

00:51:37.183 --> 00:51:37.890
happens.

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:40.251
So this type of information
is helpful for us.

00:51:40.251 --> 00:51:42.500
If we want to, for instance,
introduce new information

00:51:42.500 --> 00:51:43.970
on the screen,
we'd want to know,

00:51:43.970 --> 00:51:45.230
hey, are we going
to introduce this

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:47.700
in a place that's going to get
a lot of traffic naturally.

00:51:47.700 --> 00:51:49.400
But also is it going
to interrupt things

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:52.667
that that gaze is there for
a very important reason,

00:51:52.667 --> 00:51:54.250
and maybe we shouldn't
interrupt that.

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:58.162
So we can help us to inform
those types of decisions.

00:51:58.162 --> 00:52:00.120
There's also many other
types of physiological,

00:52:00.120 --> 00:52:02.350
and I'll just hint at
one right now which

00:52:02.350 --> 00:52:05.760
is things like galvanic
skin response, anything that

00:52:05.760 --> 00:52:08.600
has to do with
physiological arousal,

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:10.790
either for stress or excitement.

00:52:10.790 --> 00:52:13.250
These can help with situations
where maybe players wouldn't

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:15.380
be able to vocalize
why something

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:17.710
was frustrating or exciting.

00:52:17.710 --> 00:52:19.840
Or it can also help
combat some biases

00:52:19.840 --> 00:52:21.980
like recency
effect, where if you

00:52:21.980 --> 00:52:23.790
ask a player at
the end of the lab

00:52:23.790 --> 00:52:26.014
or at the end of a play
test what was interesting

00:52:26.014 --> 00:52:27.930
or what was frustrating,
they might preference

00:52:27.930 --> 00:52:29.440
things that were at the end.

00:52:29.440 --> 00:52:32.540
Or they might preference things
that were really emotionally

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:35.400
significant for them, but might
forget smaller things that

00:52:35.400 --> 00:52:38.580
are still maybe small
frustrating things that

00:52:38.580 --> 00:52:41.431
build up over time.

00:52:41.431 --> 00:52:43.180
So none of this is
really that interesting

00:52:43.180 --> 00:52:45.820
if I don't give you an example
of how we actually do at Riot.

00:52:45.820 --> 00:52:47.000
So here's a case study.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:50.859
And I actually presented this
last year as part of a talk

00:52:50.859 --> 00:52:51.650
that we did at MIT.

00:52:51.650 --> 00:52:54.760
So I apologize if a little
bit is re-run for you guys.

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:57.531
I'll try to spice it up
a little bit as I go.

00:52:57.531 --> 00:52:59.905
So I'm going to be talking
about Lucian, who I introduced

00:52:59.905 --> 00:53:00.920
to you guys earlier.

00:53:00.920 --> 00:53:03.250
He is one of the player
characters or champions

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:06.760
in League of Legends.

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:08.594
So where we always
start as researchers,

00:53:08.594 --> 00:53:10.760
and part of the job that I
haven't really alluded to

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:14.070
yet is we spend a lot of time
talking to our designers,

00:53:14.070 --> 00:53:16.480
to our developers, to our
artists, to our producers,

00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:18.027
to make sure we
understand the goals

00:53:18.027 --> 00:53:19.110
they're trying to achieve.

00:53:19.110 --> 00:53:20.110
And I don't know
how many of you guys

00:53:20.110 --> 00:53:22.460
got to catch August
Browning's talk last night,

00:53:22.460 --> 00:53:24.030
but for the champion
designers, they

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:26.867
start with a very specific
idea of what goals

00:53:26.867 --> 00:53:27.950
they're trying to achieve.

00:53:27.950 --> 00:53:29.980
What is this player
character going to feel like?

00:53:29.980 --> 00:53:32.021
What are you going to feel
like when you play it?

00:53:32.021 --> 00:53:34.130
What is the mechanics
supposed to feel like?

00:53:34.130 --> 00:53:35.870
What is the theme
supposed to feel like?

00:53:35.870 --> 00:53:37.150
How does this
resonate with players?

00:53:37.150 --> 00:53:38.350
How does it fit in
League of Legends?

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:40.391
These are all really
important questions for them

00:53:40.391 --> 00:53:43.081
that they're constantly
asking themselves.

00:53:43.081 --> 00:53:44.830
And in the case of
Lucian, he was supposed

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:47.250
to feel fast, sleek, speedy.

00:53:47.250 --> 00:53:48.440
He was like a gun ninja.

00:53:48.440 --> 00:53:49.841
Like pew, pew.

00:53:49.841 --> 00:53:50.340
No?

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:51.900
All right.

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:53.950
Trying to see if you
guys were awake there.

00:53:53.950 --> 00:53:56.080
And he's a range
damage character

00:53:56.080 --> 00:53:57.480
with finesse game play.

00:53:57.480 --> 00:54:02.280
And he basically has
the high skill ceiling.

00:54:02.280 --> 00:54:05.220
And what that means is basically
he's harder to pick up,

00:54:05.220 --> 00:54:08.370
but when you master him it's
a really rewarding feeling.

00:54:08.370 --> 00:54:11.250
So that's a trade off
between accessibility, maybe

00:54:11.250 --> 00:54:12.860
how quickly a player
can pick him up,

00:54:12.860 --> 00:54:14.810
or what level a player
can pick him up,

00:54:14.810 --> 00:54:17.050
for a reward of how
rewarding that feels when

00:54:17.050 --> 00:54:19.180
you do master that champion.

00:54:19.180 --> 00:54:22.407
And some of the challenges in
this were, this guy, his theme

00:54:22.407 --> 00:54:23.240
is pretty different.

00:54:23.240 --> 00:54:26.480
His equilibrium style, if
you've ever seen that movie.

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:28.480
And that's not something
we had necessarily

00:54:28.480 --> 00:54:30.271
done that much in League
of Legends before,

00:54:30.271 --> 00:54:32.510
so we wanted to make
sure, does he even fit.

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:34.135
And we also wanted
to know how do

00:54:34.135 --> 00:54:37.210
you let a player feel super
fast and speedy in what

00:54:37.210 --> 00:54:39.230
is essentially an
RTS style game.

00:54:39.230 --> 00:54:42.580
It's a challenge.

00:54:42.580 --> 00:54:45.680
So this is what the test
plan eventually looked like.

00:54:45.680 --> 00:54:47.990
It's not necessarily
where we started from.

00:54:47.990 --> 00:54:49.685
But we started with
concept testing,

00:54:49.685 --> 00:54:51.810
and then we went through
actually three lab studies

00:54:51.810 --> 00:54:53.780
with iteration in between
based on the feedback

00:54:53.780 --> 00:54:55.110
we got from players.

00:54:55.110 --> 00:54:59.990
And after he launched, we did
some post-launch evaluation.

00:54:59.990 --> 00:55:01.880
So step one, just like
I showed you earlier,

00:55:01.880 --> 00:55:03.210
was to do this concept testing.

00:55:03.210 --> 00:55:07.850
And we got some pretty good
feedback based on that.

00:55:07.850 --> 00:55:09.620
His fantasy was
good with players.

00:55:09.620 --> 00:55:10.520
They liked the mood.

00:55:10.520 --> 00:55:10.850
[THUD]

00:55:10.850 --> 00:55:11.770
They felt like he fit.

00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:12.793
Are you all right?

00:55:12.793 --> 00:55:14.482
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:55:14.482 --> 00:55:15.940
GENEVIEVE CONLEY:
And he made sense

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:18.340
for the role of an AD carry,
which again is like a range

00:55:18.340 --> 00:55:20.180
damage dealer in this case.

00:55:20.180 --> 00:55:23.120
So he had high appeal scores and
the theme felt really strong,

00:55:23.120 --> 00:55:25.250
but one thing we very
quickly identified--

00:55:25.250 --> 00:55:26.874
it's a little hard
to see on this one--

00:55:26.874 --> 00:55:28.660
but his guns were
different colors.

00:55:28.660 --> 00:55:31.060
So players expected the
guns to do different things

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:33.670
based on their colors, which
was not what we were planning.

00:55:33.670 --> 00:55:35.170
So this was very
good early feedback

00:55:35.170 --> 00:55:37.045
before we got very far
into development where

00:55:37.045 --> 00:55:39.290
we could pivot and make sure
that the idea of the two

00:55:39.290 --> 00:55:42.330
guns doing the same
thing was conveyed.

00:55:42.330 --> 00:55:44.016
So based on the
feedback we got, we

00:55:44.016 --> 00:55:45.640
were able to give
that to the designers

00:55:45.640 --> 00:55:47.800
and they continued
their development.

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:49.550
And then after a
little bit of time,

00:55:49.550 --> 00:55:51.250
we were able to take
it into the lab.

00:55:51.250 --> 00:55:53.190
So we started with a
Lucian that was designed

00:55:53.190 --> 00:55:54.980
to be a speedy range assassin.

00:55:54.980 --> 00:55:58.130
He had a double shot
and a utility kit.

00:55:58.130 --> 00:55:59.880
And when I refer to
kit, just to be clear,

00:55:59.880 --> 00:56:01.640
that means his set of abilities.

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:03.140
And characters in
League of Legends

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:05.830
generally have three abilities
and then an ultimate ability,

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:08.280
where the ultimate is like
the super big bad power

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:11.530
that you get after some
leveling of the character.

00:56:11.530 --> 00:56:14.870
So I blew the reveal
here, but in the first lab

00:56:14.870 --> 00:56:18.140
we found out that he didn't
really feel that sleek

00:56:18.140 --> 00:56:18.810
and fast.

00:56:18.810 --> 00:56:19.840
He felt stiff.

00:56:19.840 --> 00:56:22.940
He planted and then fired
his double shot, which

00:56:22.940 --> 00:56:25.220
made him feel like a turret.

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:26.990
And people did like
his visual theme.

00:56:26.990 --> 00:56:28.781
They thought it was
compelling, but it just

00:56:28.781 --> 00:56:30.790
didn't match his play style.

00:56:30.790 --> 00:56:33.500
So we took this back to the
designers we said, hey guys.

00:56:33.500 --> 00:56:34.550
Here's the videos.

00:56:34.550 --> 00:56:35.587
Here's the notes.

00:56:35.587 --> 00:56:37.170
We usually make a
highlight reel based

00:56:37.170 --> 00:56:39.052
on what we see to
support our evidence so

00:56:39.052 --> 00:56:41.260
that the designers can get
enough feedback from that,

00:56:41.260 --> 00:56:43.060
as they are our
subject matter experts

00:56:43.060 --> 00:56:45.924
and really know how to
interpret what they see.

00:56:45.924 --> 00:56:46.590
And we said, OK.

00:56:46.590 --> 00:56:47.450
Let's go back.

00:56:47.450 --> 00:56:49.300
You guys take some
time, do some changes.

00:56:49.300 --> 00:56:51.250
We'll take it in the lab again.

00:56:51.250 --> 00:56:52.290
So we did lab study two.

00:56:52.290 --> 00:56:54.780
And this time, we had a
different Lucian to bring in.

00:56:54.780 --> 00:56:56.100
This time, he was more mobile.

00:56:56.100 --> 00:56:58.060
He was basically a
range [INAUDIBLE],

00:56:58.060 --> 00:57:01.740
running gun, double shot guy.

00:57:01.740 --> 00:57:04.760
Well, we had a little bit of
a mixed bag of results here.

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:07.820
He did feel a little bit faster.

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:11.430
But some poses and
animations felt awkward.

00:57:11.430 --> 00:57:14.611
And he was high speed
in the numbers-- which

00:57:14.611 --> 00:57:16.360
I'll talk about in a
second-- but he still

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:18.580
felt slow for some reason.

00:57:18.580 --> 00:57:21.550
But worst of all, we
got quotes like this one

00:57:21.550 --> 00:57:23.120
about the ultimate,
which was "It

00:57:23.120 --> 00:57:25.720
worked in the way I did
not want it to work,"

00:57:25.720 --> 00:57:29.607
which is a pretty good sign
that something's wrong.

00:57:29.607 --> 00:57:31.440
So we took all this
back to designers again.

00:57:31.440 --> 00:57:33.100
We said, hey guys--
and the animators

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:35.349
and the artists in this case,
of course-- and we said,

00:57:35.349 --> 00:57:36.040
he feels slow.

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:37.440
His ultimate doesn't
really have the usability

00:57:37.440 --> 00:57:39.930
that people expect, but the
double shot theme is working,

00:57:39.930 --> 00:57:41.513
so we're definitely
on the right track

00:57:41.513 --> 00:57:44.440
and players are still very
excited about this champion.

00:57:44.440 --> 00:57:46.760
So now we're in a
bind, and this is often

00:57:46.760 --> 00:57:50.220
the case when you're working
with research from players

00:57:50.220 --> 00:57:52.185
because they're not
always able to articulate

00:57:52.185 --> 00:57:53.810
exactly what's wrong
because they don't

00:57:53.810 --> 00:57:55.526
have the context that you do.

00:57:55.526 --> 00:57:57.150
So this is why it's
so important for us

00:57:57.150 --> 00:57:59.740
as researchers to pair with
our designers, our artists,

00:57:59.740 --> 00:58:02.130
our producers, and
our players to be

00:58:02.130 --> 00:58:03.840
able to get the
right kind of data

00:58:03.840 --> 00:58:05.800
to make informed decisions.

00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:07.870
So here was our problem.

00:58:07.870 --> 00:58:10.240
The frame delay between
his basic attacks--

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:13.330
which is actually very,
very low in this last lab.

00:58:13.330 --> 00:58:15.620
Usually that means
things feel fast.

00:58:15.620 --> 00:58:18.920
It's a pretty standard way when
we're developing characters

00:58:18.920 --> 00:58:21.280
to be like, OK, this
will feel faster.

00:58:21.280 --> 00:58:24.520
He also had a very high
base movement speed,

00:58:24.520 --> 00:58:27.650
which means that the time it
took him to run from point A

00:58:27.650 --> 00:58:29.900
to point B was
pretty high relative

00:58:29.900 --> 00:58:31.286
to the rest of our champions.

00:58:31.286 --> 00:58:32.910
And if that weren't
enough, he actually

00:58:32.910 --> 00:58:35.090
had a dash ability which
means that he could just

00:58:35.090 --> 00:58:37.120
jump basically from
one point to another.

00:58:37.120 --> 00:58:40.540
All of these things should
have made him feel fast.

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:42.660
But players were saying
he didn't feel fast,

00:58:42.660 --> 00:58:45.840
so there was something wrong.

00:58:45.840 --> 00:58:49.590
So our designers and our
artists and our producers

00:58:49.590 --> 00:58:52.660
took all of this information
back, looked at the videos,

00:58:52.660 --> 00:58:56.760
play tested the heck out of it,
and came to this conclusion.

00:58:56.760 --> 00:58:59.410
They increased the
ability responsiveness

00:58:59.410 --> 00:59:03.050
and they changed how animation
flowed from one state

00:59:03.050 --> 00:59:04.030
to another.

00:59:04.030 --> 00:59:05.727
So I'm not an
artist, but what this

00:59:05.727 --> 00:59:07.310
means to me is that
they are basically

00:59:07.310 --> 00:59:10.860
able to make the transitions
from animation a, animation

00:59:10.860 --> 00:59:13.490
b, or ability a to
ability b, and make

00:59:13.490 --> 00:59:15.450
those feel more natural.

00:59:15.450 --> 00:59:17.020
Not like me.

00:59:17.020 --> 00:59:22.510
And they also gave more
feedback to the double shot.

00:59:22.510 --> 00:59:24.690
And again, this is where
subject matter expertise is

00:59:24.690 --> 00:59:27.790
so important because our
animators, our visual artists,

00:59:27.790 --> 00:59:30.300
our designers knew
this bag of tricks

00:59:30.300 --> 00:59:32.780
to be able to apply to it.

00:59:32.780 --> 00:59:34.640
And finally, they
were able to make

00:59:34.640 --> 00:59:36.370
the ultimate ability clearer.

00:59:36.370 --> 00:59:37.860
So they were able
to the telegraph

00:59:37.860 --> 00:59:39.760
better what it was
actually supposed

00:59:39.760 --> 00:59:44.120
to do so that players would
have more accurate expectations.

00:59:44.120 --> 00:59:46.330
So we took it to lab
study number three.

00:59:46.330 --> 00:59:48.815
We put it in and
finally, the game

00:59:48.815 --> 00:59:50.910
play anesthetics
fit the concept,

00:59:50.910 --> 00:59:52.810
and players were quite happy.

00:59:52.810 --> 00:59:55.500
But not everything is
always happy ending,

00:59:55.500 --> 00:59:56.990
everything is perfect.

00:59:56.990 --> 01:00:00.080
There was still some confusion
about how the ultimate was

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:01.790
supposed to work.

01:00:01.790 --> 01:00:03.950
We found that players
wanted more control of it.

01:00:03.950 --> 01:00:05.700
Basically how the
ultimate currently works

01:00:05.700 --> 01:00:09.140
is he locks his arms forward
and shoots in that direction.

01:00:09.140 --> 01:00:10.839
So if you stray
left to right, he

01:00:10.839 --> 01:00:12.630
continues shooting in
that direction which,

01:00:12.630 --> 01:00:14.570
for some players,
was pretty confusing.

01:00:14.570 --> 01:00:17.250
Now what they expected based
on some of our other champions,

01:00:17.250 --> 01:00:20.249
and it wasn't able for them
to learn it in one session.

01:00:20.249 --> 01:00:22.165
So one of the things
that we have to take away

01:00:22.165 --> 01:00:25.590
from that is labs have some
external validity problems,

01:00:25.590 --> 01:00:28.020
which basically means that
we're sitting in a lab.

01:00:28.020 --> 01:00:29.470
There's not other
players around.

01:00:29.470 --> 01:00:31.250
They're often not
playing on live.

01:00:31.250 --> 01:00:33.500
There's a lot of things that
are different in our test

01:00:33.500 --> 01:00:35.132
situations than real life.

01:00:35.132 --> 01:00:36.590
Usually, you wouldn't
try to master

01:00:36.590 --> 01:00:38.200
a champion in one session.

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:40.380
So this is one of those
cases where we put it out

01:00:40.380 --> 01:00:43.430
to our designers and they
decided, and we supported,

01:00:43.430 --> 01:00:47.822
that he was going to be a high
skill ceiling champion, which

01:00:47.822 --> 01:00:49.780
meant that players were
going to need some time

01:00:49.780 --> 01:00:51.060
to learn how to play him.

01:00:51.060 --> 01:00:53.590
And that just because they
didn't learn him in one session

01:00:53.590 --> 01:00:55.714
didn't mean that they
wouldn't learn him over time.

01:00:59.050 --> 01:01:03.560
So this is what Lucian looked
like when he did go live.

01:01:03.560 --> 01:01:05.067
And it helps if
I play the video.

01:01:08.710 --> 01:01:10.120
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:01:10.120 --> 01:01:11.060
[WARFARE SOUNDS]

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:14.039
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: So
he's in the top there.

01:01:14.039 --> 01:01:15.971
Pew, pew.

01:01:15.971 --> 01:01:19.352
[WARFARE SOUNDS]

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:24.720
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: So you
can see his dash there.

01:01:28.504 --> 01:01:30.099
[END PLAYBACK]

01:01:30.099 --> 01:01:32.390
GENEVIEVE CONLEY: So yeah,
sometimes a little confusing

01:01:32.390 --> 01:01:33.806
if you don't play
the game to have

01:01:33.806 --> 01:01:36.480
to watch 10 champions all in
one little team fight like that.

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:38.350
But ultimately, the
important part's there.

01:01:38.350 --> 01:01:40.914
He's using his ultimate
and he dashed at the end.

01:01:40.914 --> 01:01:42.580
Ultimately, ended up
actually delivering

01:01:42.580 --> 01:01:44.400
on player expectations
for this champion.

01:01:44.400 --> 01:01:45.577
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

01:01:45.577 --> 01:01:46.160
[END PLAYBACK]

01:01:46.160 --> 01:01:49.210
We don't need to
watch that again.

01:01:49.210 --> 01:01:50.440
So what did we learn?

01:01:50.440 --> 01:01:52.220
Well, we knew going
into it that Lucian

01:01:52.220 --> 01:01:54.304
was going to be a difficult
champion to get right.

01:01:54.304 --> 01:01:55.720
And we also learned
that, you know

01:01:55.720 --> 01:01:58.530
what, it's OK to take a champion
back to the lab multiple times

01:01:58.530 --> 01:02:01.837
if we really feel that
it's worth the effort.

01:02:01.837 --> 01:02:03.420
We knew that his
theme was compelling,

01:02:03.420 --> 01:02:05.700
but there was something
that wasn't just matching up

01:02:05.700 --> 01:02:08.712
between his mechanics, his
visuals, and his theme.

01:02:08.712 --> 01:02:11.170
And this is one of those things
is that everything on paper

01:02:11.170 --> 01:02:14.360
can be totally 100%
right, but if players

01:02:14.360 --> 01:02:16.547
don't agree with it or
players aren't feeling

01:02:16.547 --> 01:02:18.130
those goals that
you're trying to hit,

01:02:18.130 --> 01:02:19.830
there's going to be a problem.

01:02:19.830 --> 01:02:22.270
So we're able to collaborate
with our subject matter

01:02:22.270 --> 01:02:24.630
experts, with our
players, in order

01:02:24.630 --> 01:02:27.230
to get the experience right.

01:02:27.230 --> 01:02:30.470
And I mean, I'll say it again.

01:02:30.470 --> 01:02:32.620
Just because the mechanics
stacked up correctly

01:02:32.620 --> 01:02:34.330
does not mean that
it necessarily will

01:02:34.330 --> 01:02:37.020
in the feeling, which is why
you play test it in house,

01:02:37.020 --> 01:02:39.280
why you play test it with
other people at your studio

01:02:39.280 --> 01:02:41.630
or at your school, and
ideally, why you test it

01:02:41.630 --> 01:02:44.650
with the people who are actually
going to play your game.

01:02:44.650 --> 01:02:46.780
And then we also learned
that you can sometimes

01:02:46.780 --> 01:02:48.280
have these trade-offs.

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:51.060
It goes back to what
you hear from players.

01:02:51.060 --> 01:02:52.950
Sometimes they're going
to make suggestions

01:02:52.950 --> 01:02:55.140
and you have to look for
the note behind the note.

01:02:55.140 --> 01:02:56.904
It's like, what is
actually the problem?

01:02:56.904 --> 01:02:58.570
You guys are the
subject matter experts.

01:02:58.570 --> 01:03:00.819
You're going to be able to
look at what they're saying

01:03:00.819 --> 01:03:03.820
and never take it as,
from players, a criticism.

01:03:03.820 --> 01:03:06.630
Always think about it as if
they said something wrong,

01:03:06.630 --> 01:03:09.170
there's something that has
to be causing the problem.

01:03:09.170 --> 01:03:11.070
What is it underneath
their note that's

01:03:11.070 --> 01:03:12.660
actually causing that problem?

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:13.880
Let's look for that thing.

01:03:16.630 --> 01:03:18.850
And we're still
iterating after launch.

01:03:18.850 --> 01:03:21.590
That's one thing that's typical
with our champions is that yes,

01:03:21.590 --> 01:03:22.840
we do play tests with players.

01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:25.160
Yes, we do play tests in house.

01:03:25.160 --> 01:03:27.300
But once we launch
the champion, there

01:03:27.300 --> 01:03:29.600
are thousands and
thousands of play tests

01:03:29.600 --> 01:03:31.699
with real players on live.

01:03:31.699 --> 01:03:33.990
And that's when we learn
about things that happen maybe

01:03:33.990 --> 01:03:37.080
at scale or under very
specific situations,

01:03:37.080 --> 01:03:38.900
or for things that we
didn't account for,

01:03:38.900 --> 01:03:41.330
for these external
validity concerns.

01:03:41.330 --> 01:03:43.020
So we keep iterating.

01:03:43.020 --> 01:03:44.640
And in the case of
Lucian, we actually

01:03:44.640 --> 01:03:47.360
continue to collect
metrics and user sentiment

01:03:47.360 --> 01:03:49.570
through things like surveys
and through game data

01:03:49.570 --> 01:03:51.309
to understand how he was doing.

01:03:51.309 --> 01:03:52.850
And based on this,
we're able to make

01:03:52.850 --> 01:03:54.990
more iterations, fine
tune, and hopefully

01:03:54.990 --> 01:03:57.300
make him a little
bit more accessible.

01:03:57.300 --> 01:03:59.790
And today, Lucian is well
regarded, widely played.

01:03:59.790 --> 01:04:01.520
And if you watch the
professional matches

01:04:01.520 --> 01:04:04.364
in the world championship,
he's use quite frequently.

01:04:04.364 --> 01:04:06.280
All right, you guys, I
hope I didn't bore you.

